<TITLE> Prince Charles saves house, furniture for public </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, June 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's Prince Charles has successfully led efforts to rescue a famous Scottish stately home and its historic contents from being sold at auction, and will open its doors to the public possibly next year. The heir to the throne brought together a group of charitable organizations and donors to raise some of the cash required to fund the acquisition of Dumfries House, an important 18th century classical house in Scotland. The Prince's Charities Foundation borrowed a 'considerable proportion' of the 45 million pounds ($90 million) total cost of the project, which includes opening the house to the public in 2008 and maintaining it. Christie's had been due to auction the contents of the house this month and the house was to be sold off by estate agents Savills. Owner John Bute originally planned to sell it in order to "devolve modern assets to the next generation of my family". The auctioneer expected to set a new record for a piece of British furniture when a Thomas Chippendale rosewood bookcase went under the hammer as part of the Dumfries sale. The piece, made in 1759, was expected to fetch between 2 and 4 million pounds ($4-8 million). Dumfries holds what Christie's has called the most important collection of Rococo furniture by Chippendale still in private hands. The Palladian mansion was built between 1754 and 17
